04999nam a22007815i 9781400835973DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008359737 a10.1515/97814008359732doi  a(DE-B1597)446671  a(OCoLC)979749457  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a1702231 aBruckner, Pascal, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPerpetual Euphoria :bOn the Duty to Be Happy /cPascal Bruckner.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Invisible Penitence -- tPart I. Paradise Is Where I Am -- tChapter one. Life as a Dream and a Lie -- tChapter two. The Golden Age and After? -- tChapter 3. The Disciplines of Beatitude -- tPart II. The Kingdom of the Lukewarm, or The Invention of Banality -- tChapter four. The Bittersweet Saga of Dullness -- tChapter five. The Extremists of Routine -- tChapter six. Real Life Is Not Absent -- tPart III. The Bourgeoisie, or The Abjection of Well-Being -- tChapter seven. The Fat, Prosperous Elevation of the Average, the Mediocre” -- tChapter eight. What Is Happiness for Some Is Kitsch for Others -- tChapter nine. If Money Doesn’t Make You Happy, Give It Back! -- tPart IV. Unhappiness Outlawed? -- tChapter ten. The Crime of Suffering -- tChapter eleven. Impossible Wisdom -- tConclusion. Madame Verdurin’s Croissant -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHappiness today is not just a possibility or an option but a requirement and a duty. To fail to be happy is to fail utterly. Happiness has become a religion--one whose smiley-faced god looks down in rebuke upon everyone who hasn't yet attained the blessed state of perpetual euphoria. How has a liberating principle of the Enlightenment--the right to pursue happiness--become the unavoidable and burdensome responsibility to be happy? How did we become unhappy about not being happy--and what might we do to escape this predicament? In Perpetual Euphoria, Pascal Bruckner takes up these questions with all his unconventional wit, force, and brilliance, arguing that we might be happier if we simply abandoned our mad pursuit of happiness. Gripped by the twin illusions that we are responsible for being happy or unhappy and that happiness can be produced by effort, many of us are now martyring ourselves--sacrificing our time, fortunes, health, and peace of mind--in the hope of entering an earthly paradise. Much better, Bruckner argues, would be to accept that happiness is an unbidden and fragile gift that arrives only by grace and luck. A stimulating and entertaining meditation on the unhappiness at the heart of the modern cult of happiness, Perpetual Euphoria is a book for everyone who has ever bristled at the command to "be happy."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHappinessvSocial aspects. 0aHappinessxHistoryx19th century. 0aHappinessxHistoryx20th century. 0aHappinessxHistoryy19th century. 0aHappinessxHistoryy20th century. 0aHappinessxSocial aspects. 0aPHILOSOPHYvEthics &ampxMoral Philosophy. 0aPHILOSOPHYvPolitical. 0aPHILOSOPHYvSocial. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh1 aRendall, Steven.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140083597340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400835973423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400835973.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL